@a4 60
grid point in the  same  gridspace  that  is  traversed  by  _cm­
nd(EvalMesh).  Calling _cmnd(EvalPoint1) is equivalent to calling

glEvalCoord1( i$^cdot^DELTA u ~+~ u sub 1$ );

where

$DELTA u ~=~ ( u sub 2 - u sub 1 ) ^/^ n$

and $n$, $u sub 1$, and $u sub 2$ are the arguments to  the  most
recent  _cmnd(MapGrid1)  command.   The  one absolute numeric re­
quirement is that if $i~=~n$, then the  value  computed  from  $i
^cdot^ DELTA u ~+~ u sub 1$ is exactly $u sub 2$.  In the two-di­
mensional case, _cmnd(EvalPoint2), let
$DELTA u ~=~ mark ( u sub 2 - u sub 1 ) ^/^ n$

$DELTA v ~=~ mark ( v sub 2 - v sub 1 ) ^/^ m,$
where $n$, $u sub 1$, $u sub 2$, $m$, $v sub 1$, and  $v  sub  2$
are  the  arguments  to  the most recent _cmnd(MapGrid2) command.
Then the _cmnd(EvalPoint2) command is equivalent to calling

glEvalCoord2( i$^cdot^DELTA u ~+~ u sub 1$, j$^cdot^DELTA v ~+~ v sub 1$ );

The only absolute numeric requirements are that if $i~=~n$,  then
the  value computed from $i ^cdot^DELTA u ~+~ u sub 1$ is exactly
$u sub 2$, and if  $j~=~m$,  then  the  value  computed  from  $i
^cdot^DELTA v ~+~ v sub 1$ is exactly $v sub 2$.  _cmnd(Get) with

